The '''Martin Werhand Verlag''' is a German publishing house with a focus on contemporary literature and poetry.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_DS3oAEACAAJ&dq=K%C3%BCrschners+Deutscher+Literatur-Kalender+2014&hl=de&sa=X&ei=z9MFVKfjKrKM4gSRuoGgCQ&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAA ''Martin Werhand Verlag.'' In: ''[[Kürschners Deutscher Literatur-Kalender]] 2016/2017: Band I: A-O. Band II: P-Z.'', Walter De Gruyter Incorporated, 2016, P. 1270 {{ISBN|978-3-11-045397-3}}]</ref> More than 25% of the 150 published authors have an immigrant background with parents who were born outside of Germany and have their roots in countries like the Netherlands, Greece, Spain, Croatia, Austria, Italy, Poland, Hungary, Latvia, Iran, Kazakhstan, Romania, Bulgaria, Turkey, Sri Lanka, South Korea, Russia or Uganda.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4KUnhj8o-o4C&pg=PA231&dq=martin+werhand+verlag&hl=de&sa=X&ei=75JiU8LcKOfI4ATfmIHoDg&ved=0CE8Q6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=martin%20werhand%20verlag&f=false ''Martin Werhand Verlag.''] In: Patricia M. Mazón, Reinhild Steingröver: ''Not So Plain as Black and White: Afro-German Culture and History, 1890–2000.'', [[Boydell & Brewer]], 2005, P. 231</ref> Thus is also a mirror image of the German Society. The Martin Werhand publishing house stands for tolerance, integration and openness. It is located in [[Rhineland-Palatinate]].

== Foundation ==
The Martin Werhand publishing house was founded in April 1997 by the German [[philologist]], author and editor [[Martin Werhand]].<ref>[http://www.rlb.de/cgi-bin/wwwalleg/goorppd.pl?s1=-pk01590- ''Martin Werhand'' In: [[Rheinland-Pfälzische Personendatenbank]]].</ref> Martin is the son of [[Klaus Rudolf Werhand]] a [[Neuwied]]-born [[Blacksmith]] and Art Metal Sculptor.<ref>[http://www.rlb.de/cgi-bin/wwwalleg/goorppd.pl?s1=-pk06186- ''Klaus Rudolf Werhand'' In: [[Rheinland-Pfälzische Personendatenbank]]].</ref>

The beginning history of the publishing house led across the city of [[Bonn]] and the city of [[Cologne]], the largest city of the German Federal State of [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] with two leading universities, the [[University of Bonn]] and [[University of Cologne]] from where the first anthology of poetry ''Junge Lyrik'' took its beginning in 1999.<ref>Kurzporträt: Ulrike Walden: ''Er schult sich an Schiller und Rilke – Student unterstützt junge Poeten.'' In: ''[[Kölner Stadt-Anzeiger]].'' Nr. 86, Mittwoch, 14. April 1999.</ref><ref>[https://www.worldcat.org/title/junge-dichter-zeichnen-herzen-in-die-wolken/oclc/887847771&referer=brief_results Verleger-Portrait Martin Werhand], buchreport magazin. April 2001, Ausgabe 4, 32. Jahrgang, {{ISSN|0176-8220}} -K 5446 ,Harenberg Verlag, [[Düsseldorf]], Rubrik Bücher & Autoren – "Junge Dichter zeichnen Herzen in die Wolken" von Kirsten von Hagen, P. 85–86</ref> From 1999 to 2002 the Martin Werhand publishing house has published three successful poetry volumes named ''Junge Lyrik'',<ref>[http://www.ksta.de/junge-lyrik-13963512 ''Kölner Stadt-Anzeiger'', 23. Juli 2004].</ref> ''Junge Lyrik II'' and ''Junge Lyrik III'', in each of which 750 poems were included from 50 young, previously unpublished authors. This was associated with a reading series where the authors recited their works in different towns in Germany like [[Essen]], Bonn or [[Cologne]].<ref>Susanne Schanz: ''Junge Lyrik in der Uni.'' In: ''[[Kölner Stadt-Anzeiger]]'', 18. Juli 2000.</ref> In 2003, the [[Thalia (bookstore)|Thalia bookstore]] organized via its parent company Poertgen Herder in [[Münster]] on [[World Book Day]] on 23 April a reading with the anthology series ''Junge Lyrik''.<ref>[http://www.martinwerhandverlag.de/zeitleiste/ ''Junge Lyrik reading at Poertgen Herder (Thalia bookstore) in [[Münster]] on [[World Book Day]] on 23 April 2003.'' In: ''Martin Werhand Website.'']</ref> In 2006 the [[Bremer Straßenbahn]] AG under the direction of Dr. Joachim Tuz started a visual lyrical project called ''Poetry in Motion (Poesie bewegt)'' with many of the Martin Werhand publishing house authors with their contemporary poems.<ref>[http://www.poesiebewegt.de/liste.html ''Thorsten Libotte.'' In: ''Poesie bewegt.'']</ref>

In 2014 the Martin Werhand Verlag started a poetry series called ''100 Gedichte''.<ref>[https://www.martinwerhandverlag.de/buchreihen/lyrik-reihe-100-gedichte/ Lyrik Reihe – 100 Gedichte im Martin Werhand Verlag]</ref> In 2016 the publishing house presented some new book series at [[Frankfurt Book Fair]].<ref>[https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm?method=showFullRecord&currentResultId=%22Katalog%22+and+%22Frankfurter%22+and+%22Buchmesse%22%26any&currentPosition=0 Martin Werhand Verlag im Aussteller-Katalog]: at [[Frankfurt Book Fair]] ''catalogue : 19.-23. October 2016, Frankfurter Buchmesse : Ehrengast Flandern/Niederlande = Directory / Veranstalter: Frankfurter Buchmesse GmbH'', 2016, {{ISBN|978-3-923352-90-6}}, P. 478.</ref> like ''50 zeitlose Gedichte''<ref>''[https://www.martinwerhandverlag.de/klassiker// Lyrik-Reihe: 50 zeitlose Gedichte]'' Martin Werhand Verlag</ref> or ''50 Gedichte''.<ref>''[https://www.martinwerhandverlag.de/publikationen/lyrik-reihe-50-gedichte/ Lyrik-Reihe: 50 Gedichte]'' Martin Werhand Verlag</ref> 

Renowned literary publishing houses such as [[Reclam|Reclam Verlag]] or Thienemann Verlag engage in choosing their anthologies back on the authorship of the Martin Werhand publishing house in the recent past.

== Authors ==
Among the published authors are the Bulgarian-born author [[Angela Litschev]] ([[Förderpreis für Literatur der Landeshauptstadt Düsseldorf]]) 2005,<ref>[https://www.duesseldorf.de/kulturamt/auszeichnungen/literatur.html Förderpreisträgerin für Literatur der Landeshauptstadt Düsseldorf, 2005]</ref><ref>[http://www.nrw-literatur-im-netz.de/datenbank/autoren/576-litschev-angela.html Biography Litschev, [[NRW Literatur im Netz]]] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927142011/http://www.nrw-literatur-im-netz.de/datenbank/autoren/576-litschev-angela.html |date=27 September 2013 }}</ref> the poet [[Patric Hemgesberg]], musician and writer [[Christian Jahl]], the Austrian-born theatre director and playwright [[Georgia Doll]],<ref>[http://villa-lamarelle.fr/?p=2314 French Portrait of Georgia Doll]</ref> the poet [[Meinolf Finke]],<ref>[http://www.nrw-literatur-im-netz.de/datenbank/autoren/1183-finke-meinolf.html Biography Finke] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222113958/http://www.nrw-literatur-im-netz.de/datenbank/autoren/1183-finke-meinolf.html |date=22 December 2015 }} in: [[NRW Literatur im Netz]]</ref> the writer [[Renate Freund]],<ref>[http://www.rlb.de/cgi-bin/wwwalleg/goorppd.pl?s1=-pk06382- Portrait of Renate Freund] in: [[Rheinland-Pfälzische Personendatenbank]]</ref> the Spanish-born actor [[Mario Ramos (actor)|Mario Ramos]] who won the [[Hersfeld-Preis]] in 2005, the poet [[Vera Ludwig]],<ref>[http://www.nrw-literatur-im-netz.de/datenbank/autoren/1282-ludwig-vera.html Biography Ludwig, [[NRW Literatur im Netz]]]</ref> the poet [[Thomas Bruns (Poet)|Thomas Bruns]],<ref>[http://www.nrw-literatur-im-netz.de/datenbank/autoren/1237-bruns-thomas.html Biography Bruns, [[NRW Literatur im Netz]]]</ref> the [[Haiku]]-writer [[Daniel Dölschner]], poetess and translator [[Ann Catrin Apstein-Müller]],<ref>[http://www.dichtungsring-ev.de/4_Archiv/DR36_Koerper.pdf ''Ann Catrin Apstein-Müller in Dichtungsring 36, P. 126'']</ref> Daniela Frickel of the [[University of Cologne]], the Slam Poetry artist Florian Cieslik,<ref>[http://www.slam2011.de/slam2011/teilnehmer-einzel/florian-cieslik ''Poetry Slam Meisterschaften 2011: Florian Cieslik''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413155035/http://www.slam2011.de/slam2011/teilnehmer-einzel/florian-cieslik |date=13 April 2014 }}</ref> the writer [[Andrea Heuser]] ([[Wolfgang-Weyrauch-Förderpreis]]) 2007,<ref>[http://www.perlentaucher.de/autor/andrea-heuser.html ''Andrea Heuser in: Perlentaucher'']</ref> the playwright Peter Wayand, Werner Moskopp of the [[University of Koblenz and Landau]],<ref>[https://archive.is/20140501204011/https://www.uni-koblenz-landau.de/koblenz/fb2/ik/institut/philosophie/lehrende/drwernermoskopp/moskopp%20publikationen ''Werner Moskopp in: University of Koblenz and Landau'']</ref> the poet [[Thorsten Libotte]],<ref>[http://www.nrw-literatur-im-netz.de/datenbank/autoren/1149-libotte-thorsten.html Biography Libotte, [[NRW Literatur im Netz]]] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140820162337/http://www.nrw-literatur-im-netz.de/datenbank/autoren/1149-libotte-thorsten.html |date=20 August 2014 }}</ref> the writer [[Thomas Wensing]],<ref>[http://www.nrw-literatur-im-netz.de/datenbank/autoren/1191-wensing-thomas.html Biography Wensing, [[NRW Literatur im Netz]]]</ref> the poet [[Frank Findeiß]]<ref>[http://www.nrw-literatur-im-netz.de/datenbank/autoren/1154-findeiss-frank.html Biography Findeiß, [[NRW Literatur im Netz]]]</ref> and the journalist [[Simone Augustin|Simone Roßkamp]] who won the [[Axel-Springer-Preis]] in 2005.<ref>[http://www.abendblatt.de/kultur-live/article733081/Die-Axel-Springer-Preistraeger-2004.html Axel-Springer-Preis: Simone Roßkamp in [[Hamburger Abendblatt]]]</ref>

